1. Repository Structure

├── final                          # Main Arduino deployment script
├── platform_io                    # header file
├── secret.h                       # header file
├── README.md                      # Setup and documentation manual
├── software_overview_diagram.png  # Software architecture diagram
├── flowcharts                     # Robot decision-flow diagrams
    └─ mechanical_kill_switch.png
    └─ RFID_planting.png
    └─ line_following.png
└── Testing_Calibration_Evidence   # Sensor, motor, IMU, and field-test evidence

Current development note: this repository is still maintained in PlatformIO as `src/main.cpp`. For final Arduino IDE submission, copy the validated deployment code into `final.ino` and keep `secrets.h` in the same sketch folder.

2. Required Libraries

- `MiniMessenger` - Official challenge communication library.
- `ArduinoMqttClient` - Core dependency required by MiniMessenger.
- `Motoron` - Official Pololu library for controlling the N20 dual motor shields.
- `ICM_20948` - SparkFun library for handling the 9-DOF IMU gyroscope tracking.
- `MFRC522_I2C` - Library for reading grid checkpoint RFID cards over the I2C bus.
- `Servo` - Standard Arduino library used to control the 360-degree continuous rotation micro servo.
- `Wire` and `Arduino` - Built-in core frameworks for standard I2C communication and Arduino GIGA pin mappings.

3. Setup Steps

Step 1: Configure Your Secrets File

Create a new tab in the Arduino IDE named `secrets.h` inside the sketch folder. Copy and paste the lab network credentials below:

#define WIFI_SSID "PhaseSpaceNetwork_2.4G"
#define WIFI_PASSWORD "8igMacNet"
#define BROKER_HOST "192.168.0.74"
#define BROKER_PORT 1883
#define GROUP_ID "5"
#define BOARD_ID "Thomas"

Step 2: Hardware Interfacing Checklist

Ensure all onboard modules are correctly connected to the Arduino GIGA R1.

Motoron Shields
- I2C SDA -> `SDA1`
- I2C SCL -> `SCL1`
- Lower Motoron address: `0x10`
- Upper Motoron address: `0x11`
- Lower Motoron M1 -> RF motor
- Lower Motoron M2 -> RR motor
- Lower Motoron M3 -> LR motor
- Upper Motoron M1 -> LF motor

RFID Sensor
- VCC -> `5V`
- GND -> `GND`
- SDA -> `SDA1`
- SCL -> `SCL1`
- I2C address: `0x28`

Reflectance Sensor Array
- VCC -> `3.3V`
- GND -> `GND`
- Out 1 -> `D22`
- Out 3 -> `D24`
- Out 5 -> `D26`
- Out 7 -> `D28`
- Out 9 -> `D31`
The line-following logic uses Out 1/3/5/7/9 as the main five logical points: right, slight-right, middle, slight-left, and left. Out 2/4/6/8 are available for debugging and future stability improvements.

Ultrasonic Sensors
- VCC -> `5V`
- GND -> `GND`
- Front Echo -> `D37`
- Front Trig -> `D39`
- Left Echo -> `D52`
- Left Trig -> `D44`
- Right Echo -> `D46`
- Right Trig -> `D48`

Revive Button
- One side -> `GND`
- Other side -> `D32`

Mechanical Kill Switch Button
- One side -> `GND`
- Other side -> `D45`

Status LED
- Red LED -> `D36`
- Green LED -> `D38`

Servo Motor
- Signal -> `D10`
- VCC -> `5V`
- GND -> `GND`

4. Upload and run the code

- Connect the Arduino GIGA R1 WiFi to the computer using a reliable USB-C cable.
- In the Arduino IDE, go to `Tools -> Board` and select: `Arduino Mbed OS GIGA Boards -> Arduino GIGA R1`.
- Go to `Tools -> Port` and select the active COM port assigned to the GIGA.
- Click the Verify checkmark button to compile.
- Click Upload to flash the code to the robot.
- Open Serial Monitor at `115200` baud.

For PlatformIO development, the equivalent upload command is: /Users/admin/.platformio/penv/bin/platformio run --target upload
The serial monitor command is: /Users/admin/.platformio/penv/bin/platformio device monitor -e giga_r1_m7 --port /dev/cu.usbmodem101 --baud 115200

Running and testing the Wifi kill switch
- Connect the laptop or debugging device to the lab network: `PhaseSpaceNetwork_2.4G`.
- Open the team dashboard: `http://192.168.0.74:8090/team/5`
- Use the dashboard Enable/Disable buttons to test remote safety stop.
- The robot must continuously call `messenger.loop()` inside the main loop so MiniMessenger can intercept emergency payloads.
- On emergency disable, the robot should call `stopAllMotors()` immediately.
